otal_blocking":0},"body":"### 🐛 The bug\n\nAfter introducing Nuxt SEO 5.1.3 into my project (Nuxt 4.4 / Nuxt Content 3.13, linted with @nuxt/eslint), I encountered false-positive ESLint errors in the link sections of Markdown files (e.g., `[title](url)`).\n\nThe errors consist of two types: `@stylistic/semi` (Missing semicolon) and `@stylistic/eol-last` (Newline required at end of file). These should not surface on Markdown files in the first place.\n\nBased on my investigation, `nuxt-link-checker` (bundled with Nuxt SEO) generates a virtual JS snippet `navigateTo('<url>')` without a trailing semicolon or newline for each link, joins them with `\\n`, and passes the result to ESLint as `0.js`. Any stylistic rule the consumer has enabled in its flat config is then applied to that synthetic file, and the resulting messages are mapped back onto the original Markdown link locations.\n\nhttps://github.com/harlan-zw/nuxt-link-checker/blob/a5b66754966cdd543055263a0b051e3b98b0f038/src/eslint/processor.ts#L58-L65\n\n### 🛠️ To reproduce\n\nhttps://stackblitz.com/edit/github-tpprwcdg?file=README.md\n\n### 🌈 Expected behavior\n\nThe processor should only report diagnostics from `nuxt-link-checker`'s own rules (e.g., `link-checker/valid-route`, `link-checker/valid-sitemap-link`). It should ignore any other stylistic rules from the consumer's flat config.\n\n### ℹ️ Additional context\n\nThe cleanest approach would be to filter messages by `ruleId` in `postprocess`, ensuring only this plugin's diagnostics are returned. I'm happy to open a PR for this.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/harlan-zw/nuxt-link-checker/issues/87/reactions","total_count":1,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":1,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/harlan-zw/nuxt-link-checker/issues/87/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nuxt/nuxt/issues/350